In Java, inheritance is implemented using the `AbstractClass` keyword. An abstract class can have one or more non-abstract classes as subclasses by implementing the abstract methods of the parent class. The subclass can also define its own non-abstract methods and fields. Inheritance works by creating a new class that inherits all the methods and fields from the parent class. This means that every instance of the subclass will have access to all the methods and fields of the parent class.

Here's an example:

```java
